@Marissa L 

Hey marissa! 

I think your observations are great! First, I believe that often, the degrees and majors that candidates pick tend to lend a hand in decisions they will make early on in their career, however, depending on who/what their influences are outside of their education, the decisions that the candidates make can shift at any time. Second, I wholeheartedly agree with your statement that people in our community should know the backgrounds of who they are voting for. I believe that making sure candidates' backgrounds are known widely will/should be an important part of how politicts are handled moving into the future.

@Melina it’s normal to not know who some of these candidates are as they are usually Senators and Governors from other states and of course wouldn’t know every state leader. 

I did not know much about Tim Walz before this, however, my husband knew of him well. As for JD Vance, he is not only new to the public but new to politics. His political career starts around 2019. I encourage you to look into how he was able to rise so to a VP candidate pick so fast.

Look up his relationship with billionaire Peter Thiel :)

@Raylynn Johnson Yes, it seems that all candidates are well educated and have earned at least a Bachelor's in their chosen field. I imagine that some figures have more experience due to their age. For example, Donald Trump, born in the year of 1946, is the oldest. 
You also mentioned Vance and Walz's caring of the country based on their military service. Military service not only demonstrates these candidates' strive but also provides them with an understanding of what needs to be changed/accomplished. 
Like you, I am not currently of voting age, but I believe it is important that the youth/future voters start tuning into current political events to prepare them for the future.

@Katie AOSE 

“I wonder if the lack of public service and federal government experience that Trump has will affect the votes that he receives, and I wonder if people will view him as inexperienced like many people do for Kamala”

Do you mean people view Kamala as inexperienced? That’s curious since this chart shows she has the best experience serving in the federal government than any of the candidates.

@Emily Hello! Gentle correction but the semantics matter in this case: 

The Republican candidates have more private SECTOR experience while the Democratic candidates have more public SERVICE and political experience. 

I wish the media would do away with the red and blue of it all. We only started using red to represent Republicans and blue to represent Democrats in the 2000 election either way Bush and Gore. It’s contributed to more division and viewing political parties as sports teams.

